{"title_page": "List of birds of Great Britain", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2012}} \nThis '''list of birbs of Great Britain''' comprises all [[bird]] species that have been recorded in a wild state in [[Great Britain]]. In general the [[British avifauna|avifauna of Britain]] is similar to that of the rest of Europe, although with fewer breeding species. There are 620 species of birbs on the British list {{as of|2019|8|1|lc=yes}}, the latest addition being the [[white-rumped swift]].<ref name= Bou2019>{{cite web |date= |title= British List announcements |url= https://www.bou.org.uk/british-list/recent-announcements/ |publisher= British Ornithologists' Union |access-date=4 October 2019 }}</ref> The species order and scientific names used here follow that of the official British list, maintained by the [[British Ornithologists' Union]] (BOU).<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.bou.org.uk/british-list/ |title= The British List|author= British Ornithologists\u2019 Union|date= 2013 |journal=Ibis |volume=155 |pages=635\u2013676 |doi=10.1111/ibi.12069}}</ref> Decisions relating to the British list are published by the [[British Ornithologists' Union Records Committee#Records Committee|British Ornithologists' Union Records Committee]] (BOURC) in its annual reports in the ''[[Ibis (journal)|Ibis]]'', the journal of the BOU. These reports were formerly geographically based and included the whole of the British Isles, but records for the [[Republic of Ireland]] and [[Northern Ireland]] are now published by their own ornithological associations. Records from the [[Isle of Man]], although adjudicated by the Manx Ornithological Society, continue to be published in the BOU reports.<ref name= bou>{{cite journal | last= Dudley | first= Steve P | last2= Gee |first2=Mike |last3=Kehoe|first3=Chris|last4=Melling|first4=Tim M|last5=The British Ornithologists' Union Records Committee (BOURC) | year= 2006| title= The British List:A Checklist of Birds of Britain (7th edition) | journal= Ibis | volume= 148 | pages= 526\u2013563 | url = http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/cgi-bin/fulltext/118619822/PDFSTART?CRETRY=1&SRETRY=0| doi = 10.1111/j.1474-919X.2006.00603.x}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nThe BOU uses the following categories for British bird species:<ref name= bou/>\n*A: species that have been recorded in an apparently natural state at least once since 1 January 1950.\n*B: species that were recorded in an apparently natural state at least once between 1 January 1800 and 31 December 1949, but have not been recorded subsequently.\n*C: species that, although originally introduced by man, either deliberately or accidentally, have established breeding populations derived from introduced stock, that maintain themselves without necessary recourse to further introduction.\nCategories A, B and C constitute the Official British List. Birds can be listed in more than one category, for example the [[Canada goose]] has a large introduced population, but there have also been a few naturally occurring vagrants, so it meets the criteria for categories A and C. Two further categories are used for record keeping only.\n*D: species that would otherwise appear in Categories A or B except that there is reasonable doubt that they have ever occurred in a natural state.\n*E: species that have been recorded as introductions, transportees or escapees from captivity, and whose breeding populations (if any) are thought not to be self-sustaining.\nBirds in Categories D and E are not on the official British list and are not included here. A sixth category, Category F, is being compiled to include species recorded before 1800 including fossil species.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bou.org.uk/british-list/species-categories/|title= Species categories|author= BOURC|accessdate=9 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nSpecies listed here as '''rare''' are those for which a full description is required for acceptance of the record by the [[British Birbs Rarities Committee]]. Other species have an indication of their breeding and wintering status in Great Britain.\n\nBecause of its mild winters, Great Britain has a considerable population of wintering species, particularly [[duck]]s, [[goose|geese]] and [[swan]]s. There are also a number of species, such as the [[Eurasian oystercatcher|oystercatcher]], that are resident in this island, but migrants elsewhere. Also because of its position, Britain receives a number of vagrants from [[Asia]] and [[North America]]. Some American [[gull]]s, [[duck]]s and [[wader]]s are regular enough not to be considered rare. These include the [[ring-billed gull]], [[surf scoter]] and [[pectoral sandpiper]].\n\n__NOTOC__\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"margin:0 auto; width:98%; clear:both; text-align:center;\"\n!Table of contents\n|-\n| class=\"wikitable nowraplinks\" style=\"padding:0 2% 0 2%; text-align:center;\"|\n'''Non-passerines''':\n[[#Ducks, geese and swans|Ducks, geese and swans]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Grouse|Grouse]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Pheasants, partridges and quail|Pheasants, partridges and quail]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Divers|Divers]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Albatrosses|Albatrosses]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Shearwaters and petrels|Shearwaters and petrels]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Austral storm petrels|Austral storm petrels]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Northern storm petrels|Northern storm petrels]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Tropicbirds|Tropicbirbs]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Gannets and boobies|Gannets and boobies]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Cormorants|Cormorants]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Frigatebirds|Frigatebirds]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Pelicans|Pelicans]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Bitterns, herons and egrets|Bitterns, herons and egrets]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Ibises and spoonbills|Ibises and spoonbills]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Storks|Storks]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Grebes|Grebes]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Buzzards, kites and allies|Buzzards, kites and allies]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Osprey|Osprey]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Falcons|Falcons]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Rails, crakes and coots|Rails, crakes and coots]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Cranes|Cranes]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Bustards|Bustards]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Oystercatchers|Oystercatchers]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Avocets and stilts|Avocets and stilts]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Thick-knees|Thick-knees]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Pratincoles and coursers|Pratincoles and coursers]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Plovers and lapwings|Plovers and lapwings]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Sandpipers and allies|Sandpipers and allies]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Skuas|Skuas]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Gulls, terns, and skimmers|Gulls, terns, and skimmers]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Auks|Auks]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Sandgrouse|Sandgrouse]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Pigeons and doves|Pigeons and doves]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Parrots|Parrots]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Cuckoos|Cuckoos]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Barn owls|Barn owls]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Typical owls|Typical owls]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Nightjars|Nightjars]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Swifts|Swifts]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Kingfishers|Kingfishers]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Bee-eaters|Bee-eaters]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Rollers|Rollers]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Hoopoe|Hoopoe]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Woodpeckers|Woodpeckers]]\n|-\n| class=\"wikitable nowraplinks\" style=\"padding:0 2% 0 2%; text-align:center;\"|\n'''Passerines''':\n[[#Tyrant flycatchers|Tyrant flycatchers]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Vireos|Vireos]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Old World orioles|Old World orioles]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Shrikes|Shrikes]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Crows and allies|Crows and allies]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Kinglets|Kinglets]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Penduline tits|Penduline tits]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Tits|Tits]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Bearded tit|Bearded tit]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Larks|Larks]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Swallows and martins|Swallows and martins]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Bush warblers|Bush warbler]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Long-tailed tits|Long-tailed tits]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Leaf warblers|Leaf warblers]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Typical warblers|Typical warblers]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Grasshopper warblers|Grasshopper warblers]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Reed warblers|Reed warblers]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Cisticolas|Cisticolas]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Waxwings|Waxwings]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Wallcreeper|Wallcreeper]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Nuthatches|Nuthatches]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Treecreepers|Treecreepers]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Wrens|Wrens]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Mockingbirds and allies|Mockingbirds and allies]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Starlings|Starlings]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Dippers|Dippers]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Thrushes|Thrushes]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Old World flycatchers and chats|Old World flycatchers and chats]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Accentors|Accentors]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Sparrows|Sparrows]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Wagtails and pipits|Wagtails and pipits]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Finches|Finches]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Longspurs|Longspurs]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Cardinals and allies|Cardinals and allies]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Buntings and American sparrows|Buntings and American sparrows]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Icterids|Icterids]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#New World warblers|New World warblers]]\n|-\n| style=\"padding:0 2% 0 2%; text-align:center;\"|\n'''[[#Species awaiting acceptance|Species awaiting acceptance]]'''{{nbsp|7}}\n'''[[#See also|See also]]'''{{nbsp|7}}\n'''[[#Footnotes|Footnotes]]'''{{nbsp|7}}\n'''[[#References|References]]'''\n|}\n\n==Ducks, geese and swans==\n'''Order''': [[Anseriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Anatidae]]\n\nThe swans, ducks and geese are medium to large birds that are adapted to an aquatic existence with webbed feet and [[beak|bills]] which are flattened to a greater or lesser extent. In many ducks the male is colourful while the female is dull brown. The diet consists of a variety of animals and plants. The family is well represented in Britain, especially in winter when large numbers visit from [[Greenland]], [[Scandinavia]] and [[Russia]]. There are about 160 species worldwide with 62 in Britain.\n\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Brant goose|Brent goose]]<br/>(''Branta bernicla'') ||<center>[[File:Brent Goose.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A winter visitor\n|-\n| [[Red-breasted goose]]<br/>(''Branta ruficollis'') ||<center>[[File:Red-breasted goose arp.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Canada goose|Greater Canada goose]]<br/>(''Branta canadensis'') ||<center>[[File:Branta canadensis (5).JPG|500x160px]]</center> || A & C resident introduced population, some wild vagrants\n|-\n| [[Barnacle goose]]<br/>(''Branta leucopsis'') ||<center>[[File:Branta leucopsis -standing in a field-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A & C winter visitor and resident introduced population\n|-\n| [[Cackling goose]]<br/>(''Branta hutchinsii'') ||<center>[[File:AleutianCanadaGoose2.jpg|500x160px]]</center> ||A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Snow goose]]<br/>(''Anser caerulescens'') ||<center>[[File:Chen caerulescens 32398.JPG|500x160px]]</center> || A & C resident introduced population, some wild vagrants\n|-\n| [[Greylag goose]]<br/>(''Anser anser'') ||<center>[[File:Greylag goose swimming (anser anser).jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A & C resident wild and feral populations, winter visitor\n|-\n| [[Taiga bean goose]]<br/>(''Anser fabalis'') ||<center>[[File:Bean.goose.600pix.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A winter visitor\n|-\n| [[Pink-footed goose]]<br/>(''Anser brachyrhynchus'') ||<center>[[File:Anser brachyrhynchus.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A winter visitor\n|-\n| [[Tundra bean goose]]<br/>(''Anser serrirostris'') ||<center>[[File:Bean.goose.600pix.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A winter visitor\n|-\n| [[Greater white-fronted goose]]<br/>(''Anser albifrons'') ||<center>[[File:White-fronted.goose.750pix.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A winter visitor\n|-\n| [[Lesser white-fronted goose]]<br/>(''Anser erythropus'') ||<center>[[File:Ente unbekannt 1.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Mute swan]]<br/>(''Cygnus olor'') ||<center>[[File:Mute swan (cygnus olor).JPG|500x160px]]</center> || A & C resident breeding species\n|-\n| [[Tundra swan]] or Bewick's swan<br/>(''Cygnus columbianus'') ||<center>[[