nga erythropus - Laem Pak Bia.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A winter visitor and passage migrant\n|-\n| [[Greater yellowlegs]]<br/>(''Tringa melanoleuca'') ||<center>[[File:Greater Yellowlegs2.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Common greenshank]]<br/>(''Tringa nebularia'') ||<center>[[File:Tringa nebularia - Laem Phak Bia.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species and passage migrant\n|-\n| [[Lesser yellowlegs]]<br/>(''Tringa flavipes'') ||<center>[[File:Lesser Yellowlegs.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Marsh sandpiper]]<br/>(''Tringa stagnatilis'') ||<center>[[File:Tringa stagnatilis 2 - Laem Pak Bia.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Wood sandpiper]]<br/>(''Tringa glareola'') ||<center>[[File:Wood Sandpiper Photograph By Shantanu Kuveskar.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A passage migrant & rare localised breeder in far North\n|-\n| [[Common redshank]]<br/>(''Tringa totanus'') ||<center>[[File:Common Redshank Tringa totanus.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species\n|-\n| [[Ruddy turnstone|Turnstone]]<br/>(''Arenaria interpres'') ||<center>[[File:Arenaria interpres (habitus).jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species\n|-\n| [[Wilson's phalarope]]<br/>(''Phalaropus tricolor'') ||<center>[[File:Phalaropus tricolor - breeding female.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Red-necked phalarope]]<br/>(''Phalaropus lobatus'') ||<center>[[File:Red-necked Phalarope.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A winter visitor: scarce & localised summer breeding in far North\n|-\n| [[Grey phalarope]]<br/>(''Phalaropus fulicaria'') ||<center>[[File:Phalaropus fulicarius 10.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A scarce winter visitor\n|}\n\n==Skuas==\n'''Order''': [[Charadriiformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Skua|Stercorariidae]]\n\nMedium to large seabirds with mainly grey or brown plumage, sharp claws and a hooked tip to the bill. They chase other seabirds to force them to drop their catches. There are about seven species worldwide with four in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Pomarine skua]]<br/>(''Stercorarius pomarinus'') ||<center>[[File:Stercorarius pomarinusPCCA20070623-3985B.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A passage migrant \n|-\n| [[Arctic skua]]<br/>(''Stercorarius parasiticus'') ||<center>[[File:Parasitic Jaeger.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A passage migrant and localised summer breeder\n|-\n| [[Long-tailed skua]]<br/>(''Stercorarius longicaudus'') ||<center>[[File:Long-tailed Skua (js) 26.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A passage migrant\n|-\n| [[Great skua]]<br/>(''Stercorarius skua'') ||<center>[[File:Storkjove.1.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A passage migrant and localised summer breeder\n|}\n\n==Gulls, terns, and skimmers==\n'''Order''': [[Charadriiformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Gull|Laridae]]\nMedium to large [[seabird]]s with grey, white and black plumage, webbed feet and strong bills. Many are opportunistic and adaptable feeders. \n \n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Ivory gull]]<br/>(''Pagophila eburnea'') ||<center>[[File:Ivory Gull Portrait.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Sabine's gull]]<br/>(''Xema sabini'') ||<center>[[File:Xema sabini -Iceland -swimming-8 (1).jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A scarce winter visitor\n|-\n| [[Black-legged kittiwake]]<br/>(''Rissa tridactyla'') ||<center>[[File:Rissa tridactyla (Vard\u00f8, 2012).jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A breeding summer visitor and resident species\n|-\n| [[Slender-billed gull]]<br/>(''Chroicocephalus genei'') ||<center>[[File:Larus genei.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Bonaparte's gull]]<br/>(''Chroicocephalus philadelphia'') ||<center>[[File:Larus philadelphia1.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Black-headed gull]]<br/>(''Chroicocephalus ridibundus'') ||