> || A breeding summer visitor\n|-\n| [[Eurasian reed warbler]]<br/>(''Acrocephalus scirpaceus'') ||<center>[[File:Acrocephalus scirpaceus Vlaskop cropped.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A breeding summer visitor\n|-\n| [[Great reed warbler]]<br/>(''Acrocephalus arundinaceus'') ||<center>[[File:Acrocephalus arundinaceus adult NRM.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant, has bred\n|}\n\n==Cisticolas==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Cisticolidae]]\n\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Zitting cisticola]]<br/>(''Cisticola juncidis'') ||<center>[[File:Zitting Cisticola (Breeding plumage) I- Kolkata IMG 5046.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|}\n\n==Waxwings==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Bombycillidae]]\n\nThe waxwings are a group of passerine birds characterised by soft, silky plumage and unique red tips to some of the wing feathers. There are three species worldwide, two in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Cedar waxwing]]<br/>(''Bombycilla cedrorum'') ||<center>[[File:Cedar Waxwing August 14 2012 Newfoundland PA.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Bohemian waxwing]]<br/>(''Bombycilla garrulus'') ||<center>[[File:Bombycilla garrulusII.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A winter visitor in highly varied numbers.\n|}\n\n==Wallcreeper==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Wallcreeper|Tichodromadidae]]\n\nOne species, in its own family, a visitor to Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Wallcreeper]]<br/>(''Tichodroma muraria'') ||<center>[[File:Tichodroma muraria02 cropped.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|}\n\n==Nuthatches==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Nuthatch|Sittidae]]\n\nNuthatches are small woodland birds with the unusual ability to climb down trees head-first, unlike other birds which can only go upwards. There are about twenty-four species worldwide, two in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Red-breasted nuthatch]]<br/>(''Sitta canadensis'') ||<center>[[File:Sitta canadensis CT2.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Eurasian nuthatch]]<br/>(''Sitta europaea'') ||<center>[[File:Sitta europaea Luc Viatour.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|}\n\n==Treecreepers==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Treecreeper|Certhiidae]]\n\nTreecreepers are small woodland birds, brown above and white below. They have thin, pointed, down-curved bills, which they use to extricate insects from bark. There are seven species worldwide, two in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Common treecreeper]]<br/>(''Certhia familiaris'') ||<center>[[File:Certhia familiaris 01.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|-\n| [[Short-toed treecreeper]]<br/>(''Certhia brachydactyla'') ||<center>[[File:Boomkruiper1reversed.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|}\n\n==Wrens==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Troglodytidae]]\n\nWrens are small and inconspicuous birds, except for their loud songs. They have short wings and thin down-turned bills. There are about 80 species worldwide with one in Britain.\n\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Eurasian wren|Wren]]<br/>(''Troglodytes troglodytes'') ||<center>[[File:Eurasian-Wren-Troglodytes-troglodytes.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|}\n\n==Mockingbirds and allies==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Mimidae]]\n\nMedium-sized passerine birds with long tails. Some are notable for their ability to mimic sounds such as other birds' songs. There are about 35 species worldwide. Three have occurred as vagrants in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Northern mockingbird]]<br/>(''Mimus polyglottos'') ||<center>[[File:Mimus polyglottos -Krendle Woods, Cary, North Carolina, USA-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Brown thrasher]]<br/>(''Toxostoma rufum'') ||<center>[[File:Toxostoma rufum -Garland, Texas, USA-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant (one record)\n|-\n| [[Grey catbird]]<br/>(''Dumetella carolinensis'') ||<center>[[File:Dumetella carolinensis -Brendan T. Byrne State Forest, New Jersey, USA-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant (one record)\n|}\n\n==Starlings==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Starling|Sturnidae]]\n\nStarlings are small to medium-sized passerine birds with strong feet. Their flight is strong and direct and most are very gregarious. There are about 114 species worldwide with two in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Common starling]]<br/>(''Sturnus vulgaris'') ||<center>[[File:Colourful starling.jpeg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species and winter visitor\n|-\n| [[Rosy starling]]<br/>(''Pastor roseus'') ||<center>[[File:Rosy Starling (Sturnus roseus) near Hyderabad W2 IMG 4837.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|}\n\n==Dippers==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Dipper|Cinclidae]]\n\nDark, dumpy, aquatic birds which are able to forage for food on the beds of rivers. There are five species worldwide with one in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[White-throated dipper]]<br/>(''Cinclus cinclus'') ||<center>[[File:Cinclus cinclus -Kirkcudbright, Scotland-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species\n|}\n\n==Thrushes==\n'''Order''': [[passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Thrush_(bird)|Turdidae]]\n\nThe thrushes are plump, soft-plumaged, small to medium-sized insectivores or sometimes omnivores, often feeding on the ground. Many have attractive songs. There are about 183 species worldwide, 20 in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[White's thrush]]<br/>(''Zoothera dauma'') ||<center>[[File:Zoothera dauma - Ang Khang.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Varied thrush]]<br/>(''Ixoreus naevius'') ||<center>[[File:Zoothera naevia 31224.JPG|500x160px]]</center> || A very rare vagrant (one record)\n|-\n| [[Wood thrush]]<br/>(''Hylocichla mustelina'') ||<center>[[File:Hylocichla mustelina (cropped).jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Hermit thrush]]<br/>(''Catharus guttatus'') ||<center>[[File:Hermit thrush qmnonic.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Swainson's thrush]]<br/>(''Catharus ustulatus'') ||<center>[[File:Catharus ustulatus -North Dakota-8a.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Grey-cheeked thrush]]<br/>(''Catharus minimus'') ||<center>[[File:Graycheekedthrush36.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Veery]]<br/>(''Catharus fuscescens'') ||<center>[[File:Catharus fuscescens CT.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Siberian thrush]]<br/>(''Geokichla sibirica'') ||<center>[[File:Zoothera sibirica 431.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Ring ouzel]]<br/>(''Turdus torquatus'') ||<center>[[File:Ring Ouzel.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A breeding summer visitor\n|-\n| [[Common blackbird|Blackbird]]<br/>(''Turdus merula'') ||<center>[[File:Common Blackbird.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|-\n| [[Eyebrowed thrush]]<br/>(''Turdus obscurus'') ||<center>[[File:Eyebrowed Thrush.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Dusky thrush]]<br/>(''Turdus eunomus'') ||<center>[[File:Turdus eunomus -Japan-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Naumann's thrush]]<br/>(''Turdus naumanni'') ||<center>[[File:Bandong.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Black-throated thrush]]<br/>(''Turdus atrogularis'') ||<center>[[File:Turdusatro.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Red-throated thrush]]<br/>(''Turdus ruficollis'') ||<center>[[File:Dark Throated Thrush in Temple of Heaven.JPG|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Fieldfare]]<br/>(''Turdus pilaris'') ||<center>[[File:Turdus pilaris2.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A winter visitor, rare breeder\n|-\n| [[Song thrush]]<br/>(''Turdus philomelos'') ||<center>[[File:Song Thrush Turdus philomelos.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|-\n| [[Redwing]]<br/>(''Turdus iliacus'') ||<center>[[File:Redwing Turdus iliacus.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A winter visitor, rare breeder\n|-\n| [[Mistle thrush]]<br/>(''Turdus viscivorus'') ||<center>[[File:Turdus viscivorus in Baikonur-town 001.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|-\n| [[American robin]]<br/>(''Turdus migratorius'') ||<center>[[File:Turdus-migratorius-002.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|}\n\n==Old World flycatchers and chats==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Old World flycatcher|Muscicapidae]]. Subfamily: [[Old World flycatcher|Muscicapinae]]\n\nThe flycatchers and chats are small, mainly insectivorous birds. The flycatchers fly out from a perch to catch insects in the air. There are about 297 species worldwide, 30 in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Rufous bush robin]]<br/>(''Cercotrichas galactotes'') ||<center>[[File:2009-red-backed-scrub-robin.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Asian brown flycatcher]]<br/>(''Muscicapa dauurica'') ||<center>[[File:Asian Brown Flycatcher (Muscicapa dauurica) at Periyar National Park.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Spotted flycatcher]]<br/>(''Muscicapa striata'') ||<center>[[File:Muscicapa striata 1 (Martin Mecnarowski).jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A breeding summer visitor\n|-\n| [[European robin]]<br/>(''Erithacus rubecula'') ||<center>[[File:European Robin (erithacus rubecula).JPG|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species\n|-\n| [[Siberian blue robin]]<br/>(''Larvivora cyanea'') ||<center>[[File:Luscinia cyane - Khao Yai.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Rufous-tailed robin]]<br/>(''Larvivora sibilans'') ||<center>[[File:Luscinia sibilans - Khao Yai.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Siberian rubythroat]]<br/>(''Calliope calliope'') ||<center>[[File:Luscinia calliope - Pak Chong 2.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[White-throated robin]]<br/>(''Irania gutturalis'') ||<center>[[File:Nightingale yelpin.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Red-flanked bluetail]]<br/>(''Tarsiger cyanurus'') ||<center>[[File:Ruribitakif1.JPG|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Thrush nightingale]]<br/>(''Luscinia luscinia'') ||<center>[[File:Luscinia luscinia -Gugny, Biebrza National Park, Poland-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Nightingale]]<br/>(''Luscinia megarhynchos'') ||<center>[[File:Nachtigall (Luscinia megarhynchos)-2.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A breeding summer visitor\n|-\n| [[Bluethroat]]<br/>(''Luscinia svecica'') ||<center>[[File:Luscinia svecica volgae.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A scarce migrant, occasional breeder\n|-\n| [[Red-breasted flycatcher]]<br/>(''Ficedula parva'') ||<center>[[File:Red-breasted Flycatcher.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A scarce migrant\n|-\n| [[Taiga flycatcher]]<br/>(''Ficedula albicilla'') ||<center>[[File:Ficedula parva.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Collared flycatcher]]<br/>(''Ficedula albicollis'') ||<center>[[File:Mucho\u0142\u00f3wka bia\u0142oszyja (samiec).jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[European pied flycatcher|Pied flycatcher]]<br/>(''Ficedula hypoleuca'') ||<center>[[File:Ficedula hypoleuca -Wood of Cree Nature Reserve, Scotland -male-8a.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A breeding summer visitor\n|-\n| [[Black redstart]]<br/>(''Phoenicurus ochruros'') ||<center>[[File:Hausrotschwanz Brutpflege 2006-05-21-05.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A scarce breeding resident, passage migrant & winter visitor\n|-\n| [[Common redstart]]<br/>(''Phoenicurus phoenicurus'') ||<center>[[File:Gekraagde Roodstaart 20040627.JPG|500x160px]]</center> || A breeding summer visitor\n|-\n| [[Moussier's redstart]]<br/>(''Phoenicurus moussieri'') ||<center>[[File:Phoenicurus moussieri.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Common rock thrush|Rock thrush]]<br/>(''Monticola saxatilis'') ||<center>[[File:Monsax.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Blue rock thrush]]<br/>(''Monticola solitarius'') ||<center>[[File:BlueRockTrush LaCanada.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Whinchat]]<br/>(''Saxicola rubetra'') ||<center>[[File:Saxicola rubetra -Belgium -male-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A breeding summer visitor & passage migrant\n|-\n| [[Siberian stonechat]]<br/>(''Saxicola maurus'') ||<center>[[File:Siberian Stonechat (Saxicola maura)- Male at Bharatpur I IMG 5768.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[European stonechat]]<br/>(''Saxicola rubicola'') ||<center>[[File:European Stonechat.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|-\n| [[Isabelline wheatear]]<br/>(''Oenanthe isabellina'') ||<center>[[File:Isabelline wheatear (Oenanthe isabellina) male, non-breeding.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Northern wheatear]]<br/>(''Oenanthe oenanthe'') ||<center>[[File:Northern wheatear male09.JPG|500x160px]]</center> || A breeding summer visitor & passage migrant\n|-\n| [[Pied wheatear]]<br/>(''Oenanthe pleschanka'') ||<center>[[File:Oenanthe pleschanka in Crimea.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Black-eared wheatear]]<br/>(''Oenanthe hispanica'') ||<center>[[File:45-090506-black-eared-wheatear-at-Ipsilou-Monastery-.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Desert wheatear]]<br/>(''Oenanthe deserti'') ||<center>[[File:Oenanthe deserti LipKee.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[White-crowned wheatear]]<br/>(''Oenanthe leucopyga'') ||<center>[[File:Oenanthe leucopyga.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|}\n\n==Accentors==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Prunellidae]]\n\nA small family of drab, unobtrusive, insectivorous birds with thin, pointed bills. There are thirteen species worldwide with three recorded in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Dunnock]]<br/>(''Prunella modularis'') ||<center>[[File:Dunnock crop2.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species\n|-\n| [[Alpine accentor]]<br/>(''Prunella collaris'') ||<center>[[File:Alpine accentor saganta.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Siberian accentor]]<br/>(''Prunella montanella'') ||<center>[[File:Siberian Accentor (Prunella montanella) - \u0421\u0438\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0438\u0439\u043d \u0445\u0430\u0439\u0440\u0443\u0443\u043b\u0434\u0430\u0439 (16435139700).jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant with multiple records in 2016\n|}\n\n==Sparrows==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Old World sparrow|Passeridae]]\n\nSparrows tend to be small, plump, brownish or greyish birds with short tails and short, powerful beaks. They are seed-eaters and they also consume small insects. There are about thirty-eight species worldwide, four in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[House sparrow]]<br/>(''Passer domesticus'') ||<center>[[File:House sparrow (Passer domesticus).jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|-\n| [[Spanish sparrow]]<br/>(''Passer hispaniolensis'') ||<center>[[File:Passer Hispaniolensis Male.JPG|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Eurasian tree sparrow]]<br/>(''Passer montanus'') ||<center>[[File:Tree Sparrow Japan Flip.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|-\n| [[Rock sparrow]]<br/>(''Petronia petronia'') ||<center>[[File:Petronia petronia -Ariege, Midi-Pyrenee, France-8-4c.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|}\n\n==Wagtails and pipits==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Motacillidae]]\n\nMotacillidae is a family of small passerine birds with medium to long tails. They are slender, ground-feeding insectivores of open country. There are about 66 species worldwide, 15 in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Western yellow wagtail]]<br/>(''Motacilla flava'') ||<center>[[File:Yellow Wagtail (5811285648).jpg|500x160px]]</center> || Seven races including:\n* Blue-headed wagtail ''M. f. flava'' (nominate subspecies occurring as a migrant)\n* Yellow wagtail ''M. f. flavissima'' (subspecies breeding in Britain)\n|-\n| [[Citrine wagtail]]<br/>(''Motacilla citreola'') ||<center>[[File:Citrine Wagtail (Motacilla citreola)- Breeding Male of calcarata race at Bharatpur I IMG 5752.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Grey wagtail]]<br/>(''Motacilla cinerea'') ||<center>[[File:Grey Wagtail.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species\n|-\n| [[White wagtail]]<br/>(''Motacilla alba'') ||<center>[[File:Pied Wagtail rear view 700.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species with two additional visiting races\n* ''M. a. alba'' (nominate subspecies occurring as a migrant)\n* ''M. a. leucopsis'', Amur wagtail (rare vagrant)\n* ''M. a. yarrelli'', pied wagtail (subspecies breeding in Britain)\n|-\n| [[Richard's pipit]]<br/>(''Anthus richardi'') ||<center>[[File:Richard's Pipit I -Haryana IMG 9961.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A scarce migrant\n|-\n| [[Blyth's pipit]]<br/>(''Anthus godlewskii'') ||<center>[[File:Blyth s Pipit Anthus godlewskii.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Tawny pipit]]<br/>(''Anthus campestris'') ||<center>[[File:AnthusCampestris cropped.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A scarce migrant\n|-\n| [[Olive-backed pipit]]<br/>(''Anthus hodgsoni'') ||<center>[[File:Olive backed Pipit.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Tree pipit]]<br/>(''Anthus trivialis'') ||<center>[[File:Anthus triviallis (Marek Szczepanek).jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A breeding summer visitor\n|-\n| [[Pechora pipit]]<br/>(''Anthus gustavi'') ||<center>[[File:Pechora Pipit spring Attu-island Alaska.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Meadow pipit]]<br/>(''Anthus pratensis'') ||<center>[[File:Meadowpippit2008 edit.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|-\n| [[Red-throated pipit]]<br/>(''Anthus cervinus'') ||<center>[[File:Red-throated Pipit.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A scarce migrant\n|-\n| [[Eurasian rock pipit|Rock pipit]]<br/>(''Anthus petrosus'') ||<center>[[File:Anthus petrosus3.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|-\n| [[Water pipit]]<br/>(''Anthus spinoletta'') ||<center>[[File:Anthus spinoletta.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A winter visitor\n|-\n| [[Buff-bellied pipit]]<br/>(''Anthus rubescens'') ||<center>[[File:Anthus rubescens -Harney County, Oregon, USA-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|}\n\n==Finches==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[finch|Fringillidae]]\n\nSeed-eating passerine birds that are small to moderately large and have a strong beak, usually conical and in some species very large. There are about 176 species worldwide, 22 in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Common chaffinch]]<br/>(''Fringilla coelebs'') ||<center>[[File:Chaffinch (Fringilla coelebs).jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|-\n| [[Brambling]]<br/>(''Fringilla montifringilla'') ||<center>[[File:Fringilla montifringilla -Poland -male-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A winter visitor, occasional breeder\n|-\n| [[European serin]]<br/>(''Serinus serinus'') ||<center>[[File:Serinus serinus (Madrid, Spain) 002.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A scarce passage migrant, occasional breeder\n|-\n| [[European greenfinch]]<br/>(''Chloris chloris'') ||<center>[[File:Greenfinch (carduelis chloris) m.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|-\n| [[Citril finch]]<br/>(''Carduelis citrinella'') ||<center>[[File:Carduelis citrinella -Plateau de Beille, Ariege, Midi-Pyrenee, France-8 (1).jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[European goldfinch]]<br/>(''Carduelis carduelis'') ||<center>[[File:Carduelis carduelis close up.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species\n|-\n| [[Eurasian linnet]]<br/>(''Linaria cannabina'') ||<center>[[File:Carduelis cannabina -England -male-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species\n|-\n| [[Twite]]<br/>(''Linaria flavirostris'') ||<center>[[File:Carduelis flavirostris.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species\n|-\n| [[Eurasian siskin]]<br/>(''Spinus spinus'') ||<center>[[File:Carduelis spinus male.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species and winter visitor\n|-\n| [[Lesser redpoll]]<br/>(''Acanthis cabaret'') ||<center>[[File:Carduelis cabaret1.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species\n|-\n| [[Mealy redpoll]]<br/>(''Acanthis flammea'') ||<center>[[File:Carduelis flammea CT6.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A winter visitor and passage migrant, occasional breeder\n|-\n| [[Arctic redpoll]]<br/>(''Acanthis hornemanni'') ||<center>[[File:Carduelis hornemanni CT3.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A scarce migrant\n|-\n| [[Two-barred crossbill]]<br/>(''Loxia leucoptera'') ||<center>[[File:Whitewingedcrossbillmale09.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Common crossbill]]<br/>(''Loxia curvirostra'') ||<center>[[File:Red Crossbills (Male).jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|-\n| [[Scottish crossbill]]<br/>(''Loxia scotica'') ||<center>[[File:Common Crossbill (Loxia curvirostra) - geograph.org.uk - 419190.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident endemic breeding species \n|-\n| [[Parrot crossbill]]<br/>(''Loxia pytyopsittacus'') ||<center>[[File:Loxia pytyopsittacus071021.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species\n|-\n| [[Trumpeter finch]]<br/>(''Bucanetes githagineus'') ||<center>[[File:Bucanetes githagineus -Salinas de Janubio, Lanzarote, Spain-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Common rosefinch]]<br/>(''Erythrina erythrinus'') ||<center>[[File:Carpodacus erythrinus 20060623.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A scarce migrant, occasional breeder\n|-\n| [[Pine grosbeak]]<br/>(''Pinicola enucleator'') ||<center>[[File:Pine grosbeak17g.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Eurasian bullfinch]]<br/>(''Pyrrhula pyrrhula'') ||<center>[[File:Pyrrhula pyrrhula -Lochwinnoch, Renfrewshire, Scotland-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species\n|-\n| [[Hawfinch]]<br/>(''Coccothraustes coccothraustes'') ||<center>[[File:Coccothraustes coccothraustes.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A scarce resident breeding species\n|-\n| [[Evening grosbeak]]<br/>(''Hesperiphona vespertinua'') ||<center>[[File:Hesperiphona vespertina CT3.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|}\n\n==Longspurs==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Emberizidae]]. Tribe: [[Calcariini]]\n\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Snow bunting]]<br/>(''Plectrophenax nivalis'') ||<center>[[File:Snow Bunting Cairngorm.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A winter visitor & scarce breeder\n|-\n| [[Lapland bunting]]<br/>(''Calcarius lapponicus'') ||<center>[[File:Lapland Longspur (Calcarius lapponicus).jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A winter visitor, occasional breeder\n|}\n\n==Cardinals and allies==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Emberizidae]]. Tribe: [[Cardinalini]]\n\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Summer tanager]]<br/>(''Piranga rubra'') ||<center>[[File:Summer Tanager male hephzibah.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Scarlet tanager]]<br/>(''Piranga olivacea'') ||<center>[[File:Piranga olivacea1.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Rose-breasted grosbeak]]<br/>(''Pheucticus ludovicianus'') ||<center>[[File:RosebreastedGrosbeak08.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Indigo bunting]]<br/>(''Passerina cyanea'') ||<center>[[File:Indigo Bunting by Dan Pancamo 4.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|}\n\n==Buntings and American sparrows==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Emberizidae]]. Tribe: [[Emberizini]]\n\nA large group of seed-eating passerine birds with a distinctively shaped bill. There are about 179 species worldwide, 24 in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Eastern towhee|Rufous-sided towhee]]<br/>(''Pipilo erythrophthalmus'') ||<center>[[File:Pipilo erythrophthalmus -Quabbin Reservoir, Massachusetts, USA -male-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Lark sparrow]]<br/>(''Chondestes grammacus'') ||<center>[[File:LarkSparrow.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Savannah sparrow]]<br/>(''Passerculus sandwichensis'') ||<center>[[File:Passerculus sandwichensis crop.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Song sparrow]]<br/>(''Melospiza melodia'') ||<center>[[File:Melospiza-melodia-001.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[White-crowned sparrow]]<br/>(''Zonotrichia leucophrys'') ||<center>[[File:White-crowned-Sparrow.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[White-throated sparrow]]<br/>(''Zonotrichia albicollis'') ||<center>[[File:Zonotrichia albicollis CT1.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Dark-eyed junco]]<br/>(''junco hyemalis'') ||<center>[[File:Junco hyemalis hyemalis CT2.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Black-faced bunting]]<br/>(''Emberiza spodocephala'') ||<center>[[File:Aoji male.JPG|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Pine bunting]]<br/>(''Emberiza leucocephalos'') ||<center>[[File:Emberiza_leucocephalos;_Baikonur-town_001.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Yellowhammer]]<br/>(''Emberiza citrinella'') ||<center>[[File:Emberiza citrinella -New Zealand -North Island-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|-\n| [[Cirl bunting]]<br/>(''Emberiza cirlus'') ||<center>[[File:Cirl bunting cropped.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|-\n| [[Rock bunting]]<br/>(''Emberiza cia'') ||<center>[[File:Emberiza cia Martien Brand.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Ortolan bunting]]<br/>(''Emberiza hortulana'') ||<center>[[File:Embhor.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A scarce migrant\n|-\n| [[Cretzschmar's bunting]]<br/>(''Emberiza caesia'') ||<center>[[File:Emberiza caesia.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Yellow-browed bunting]]<br/>(''Emberiza chrysophrys'') ||<center>[[File:Yellow-browed bunting (Emberiza chrysophrys) Eocheong Island Korea 2012.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Rustic bunting]]<br/>(''Emberiza rustica'') ||<center>[[File:Emberiza rustica2.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A scarce migrant\n|-\n| [[Chestnut-eared bunting]]<br/>(''Emberiza fucata'') ||<center>[[File:Emberiza fucata.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Little bunting]]<br/>(''Emberiza pusilla'') ||<center>[[File:Little Bunting.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A scarce migrant\n|-\n| [[Yellow-breasted bunting]]<br/>(''Emberiza aureola'') ||<center>[[File:EmberizaAureolaF.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Chestnut bunting]]<br/>(''Emberiza rutila'') || || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Reed bunting]]<br/>(''Emberiza schoeniclus'') ||<center>[[File:Emberiza schoeniclus -England -male-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|-\n| [[Pallas' reed bunting]]<br/>(''Emberiza pallasi'') ||<center>[[File:Emberiza pallasi (10).jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Black-headed bunting]]<br/>(''Emberiza melanocephala'') ||<center>[[File:28-090504-black-headed-bunting-at-first-layby.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Corn bunting]]<br/>(''Emberiza calandra'') ||<center>[[File:Emberiza calandra -Jardin des Plantes, Paris, France-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|}\n\n==Icterids==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Icterid|Icteridae]]. \n\nThere are four rare vagrants in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Bobolink]]<br/>(''Dolichonyx oryzivorus'') ||<center>[[File:Bobolink, Mer Bleue.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Brown-headed cowbird]]<br/>(''Molothrus ater'') ||<center>[[File:Molothrus ater 2.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Baltimore oriole]]<br/>(''Icterus galbula'') ||<center>[[File:Icterus-galbula-002.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Red-winged blackbird]]<br/>(''Agelaius phoeniceus'') ||<center>[[File:Agelaius phoeniceus2.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|}\n\n==New World warblers==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[New_World_warbler|Parulidae]]\n\nA group of small, often colourful passerine birds restricted to the New World. Most are arboreal and insectivorous. There are about 118 species worldwide. Eighteen have occurred as vagrants in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Ovenbird]]<br/>(''Seiurus aurocapilla'') ||<center>[[File:Ovenbird RWD2011b.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Northern waterthrush]]<br/>(''Parkesia noveboracensis'') ||<center>[[File:Seiurus noveboracensis MP1.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Golden-winged warbler]]<br/>(''Vermivora chrysoptera'') ||<center>[[File:Vermivora chrysoptera St Louis Missouri 1.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Black-and-white warbler]]<br/>(''Mniotilta varia'') ||<center>[[File:Black-and-white Warbler.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Tennessee warbler]]<br/>(''Oreothlypis peregrina'') ||<center>[[File:Tennessee Warbler 2.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Common yellowthroat]]<br/>(''Geothlypis trichas'') ||<center>[[File:Commonyellowthroat159.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Hooded warbler]]<br/>(''Setophaga citrina'') ||<center>[[File:Wilsonia citrina (Belize).jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[American redstart]]<br/>(''Setophaga ruticilla'') ||<center>[[File:Setophaga ruticilla -Chiquimula, Guatemala -male-8-4c.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Cape May warbler]]<br/>(''Setophaga tigrina'') ||<center>[[File:Dendroica tigrina FWS.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Northern parula]]<br/>(''Setophaga americana'') ||<center>[[File:Northern Parula in High Island by Dan Pancamo 1.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Magnolia warbler]]<br/>(''Setophaga magnolia'') ||<center>[[File:Dendroica magnolia MN.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Bay-breasted warbler]]<br/>(''Setophaga castanea'') ||<center>[[File:Dendroica-castanea-001.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Blackburnian warbler]]<br/>(''Setophaga fusca'') ||<center>[[File:Dendroica-fusca-001.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Yellow warbler]]<br/>(''Setophaga petechia'') ||<center>[[File:Dendroica-petechia-001.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Chestnut-sided warbler]]<br/>(''Setophaga pensylvanica'') ||<center>[[File:Dendroica-pensylvanica-003.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Blackpoll warbler]]<br/>(''Setophaga striata'') ||<center>[[File:BlackpollWarbler23.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Yellow-rumped warbler]]<br/>(''Setophaga coronata'') ||<center>[[File:Yellow-rump-capisic-spring-2012.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Wilson's warbler]]<br/>(''Cardellina pusilla'') ||<center>[[File:Wilsonia pusilla.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|}\n\nThe links above lead to family accounts and individual species. [[Taxonomy (biology)|Taxonomy]] is very fluid in the age of [[DNA]] analysis, so other arrangements may be found, as in [[Sibley-Ahlquist taxonomy]].\n\n==Species awaiting acceptance==\nThe following species have been recorded recently and the British Ornithologists' Union Records Committee has not yet made a decision on whether to accept them onto the British List.<ref name=BOURC37>[https://archive.today/20121216133245/http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/cgi-bin/fulltext/121577421/HTMLSTART British Ornithologists' Union 37th report (October 2008)] ''Ibis'', 151 (1): 224-230.</ref>\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Brown booby]]<br/> (''Sula leucogaster'') || || A rare vagrant \n|-\n| [[Paddyfield pipit]]<br/> (''Anthus rufulus''){{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}|| || A rare vagrant \n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of non-native birds of Great Britain]]\n* [[List of birds of Leicestershire and Rutland]]\n* [[List of birds of Wales]]\n* [[List of birds of Ireland]]\n* [[British Birds Rarities Committee]]\n* ''[[British Birds (magazine)|British Birds]]'' (a long-established ornithology journal).\n* [[Birdwatching]]\n* [[European birds]]\n* [[Ornithology]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.bou.org.uk/british-list/ List of British birds published by The British Ornithologists' Union].\n*[https://www.doi.org/10.1046/j.0019-1019.2001.00026.x Taxonomic Recommendations for European Birds]\n*[https://www.doi.org/10.1046/j.1474-919x.2002.00110.x Taxonomic recommendations for British birds] (both in PDF format).\n*[http://www.rspb.org.uk The Royal Society for the Protection of Birds (RSPB)] and [http://www.rspb.org.uk/birds/guide RSPB A to Z of UK Birds]\n*''[http://www.britishbirds.co.uk/search?id=9283 Splitting headaches? Recent taxonomic changes affecting the British and Western Palaearctic lists]'' - Martin Collinson, ''[[British Birds (magazine)|British Birds]]'' vol 99 (June 2006), 306-323\n*[http://www.bto.org/volunteer-surveys/birdatlas/previous-atlases/previous-atlases British Trust for Ornithology surveys]\n\n{{Fauna of Great Britain}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of animals of the British Isles|Bird]]\n[[Category:Birds in the United Kingdom|'01]]\n[[Category:Lists of birds by location|Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Fauna of Great Britain|'birds]]\n[[Category:Lists of birds of Europe|Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Lists of biota of Great Britain|bird]]\n[[Category:Lists of birds by country|bird]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2012}} \nThis '''list of birds of Great Britain''' comprises all [[bird]] species that have been recorded in a wild state in [[Great Britain]]. In general the [[British avifauna|avifauna of Britain]] is similar to that of the rest of Europe, although with fewer breeding species. There are 620 species of birds on the British list {{as of|2019|8|1|lc=yes}}, the latest addition being the [[white-rumped swift]].<ref name= Bou2019>{{cite web |date= |title= British List announcements |url= https://www.bou.org.uk/british-list/recent-announcements/ |publisher= British Ornithologists' Union |access-date=4 October 2019 }}</ref> The species order and scientific names used here follow that of the official British list, maintained by the [[British Ornithologists' Union]] (BOU).<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.bou.org.uk/british-list/ |title= The British List|author= British Ornithologists\u2019 Union|date= 2013 |journal=Ibis |volume=155 |pages=635\u2013676 |doi=10.1111/ibi.12069}}</ref> Decisions relating to the British list are published by the [[British Ornithologists' Union Records Committee#Records Committee|British Ornithologists' Union Records Committee]] (BOURC) in its annual reports in the ''[[Ibis (journal)|Ibis]]'', the journal of the BOU. These reports were formerly geographically based and included the whole of the British Isles, but records for the [[Republic of Ireland]] and [[Northern Ireland]] are now published by their own ornithological associations. Records from the [[Isle of Man]], although adjudicated by the Manx Ornithological Society, continue to be published in the BOU reports.<ref name= bou>{{cite journal | last= Dudley | first= Steve P | last2= Gee |first2=Mike |last3=Kehoe|first3=Chris|last4=Melling|first4=Tim M|last5=The British Ornithologists' Union Records Committee (BOURC) | year= 2006| title= The British List:A Checklist of Birds of Britain (7th edition) | journal= Ibis | volume= 148 | pages= 526\u2013563 | url = http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/cgi-bin/fulltext/118619822/PDFSTART?CRETRY=1&SRETRY=0| doi = 10.1111/j.1474-919X.2006.00603.x}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nThe BOU uses the following categories for British bird species:<ref name= bou/>\n*A: species that have been recorded in an apparently natural state at least once since 1 January 1950.\n*B: species that were recorded in an apparently natural state at least once between 1 January 1800 and 31 December 1949, but have not been recorded subsequently.\n*C: species that, although originally introduced by man, either deliberately or accidentally, have established breeding populations derived from introduced stock, that maintain themselves without necessary recourse to further introduction.\nCategories A, B and C constitute the Official British List. Birds can be listed in more than one category, for example the [[Canada goose]] has a large introduced population, but there have also been a few naturally occurring vagrants, so it meets the criteria for categories A and C. Two further categories are used for record keeping only.\n*D: species that would otherwise appear in Categories A or B except that there is reasonable doubt that they have ever occurred in a natural state.\n*E: species that have been recorded as introductions, transportees or escapees from captivity, and whose breeding populations (if any) are thought not to be self-sustaining.\nBirds in Categories D and E are not on the official British list and are not included here. A sixth category, Category F, is being compiled to include species recorded before 1800 including fossil species.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bou.org.uk/british-list/species-categories/|title= Species categories|author= BOURC|accessdate=9 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nSpecies listed here as '''rare''' are those for which a full description is required for acceptance of the record by the [[British Birds Rarities Committee]]. Other species have an indication of their breeding and wintering status in Great Britain.\n\nBecause of its mild winters, Great Britain has a considerable population of wintering species, particularly [[duck]]s, [[goose|geese]] and [[swan]]s. There are also a number of species, such as the [[Eurasian oystercatcher|oystercatcher]], that are resident in this island, but migrants elsewhere. Also because of its position, Britain receives a number of vagrants from [[Asia]] and [[North America]]. Some American [[gull]]s, [[duck]]s and [[wader]]s are regular enough not to be considered rare. These include the [[ring-billed gull]], [[surf scoter]] and [[pectoral sandpiper]].\n\n__NOTOC__\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"margin:0 auto; width:98%; clear:both; text-align:center;\"\n!Table of contents\n|-\n| class=\"wikitable nowraplinks\" style=\"padding:0 2% 0 2%; text-align:center;\"|\n'''Non-passerines''':\n[[#Ducks, geese and swans|Ducks, geese and swans]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Grouse|Grouse]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Pheasants, partridges and quail|Pheasants, partridges and quail]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Divers|Divers]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Albatrosses|Albatrosses]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Shearwaters and petrels|Shearwaters and petrels]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Austral storm petrels|Austral storm petrels]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Northern storm petrels|Northern storm petrels]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Tropicbirds|Tropicbirds]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Gannets and boobies|Gannets and boobies]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Cormorants|Cormorants]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Frigatebirds|Frigatebirds]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Pelicans|Pelicans]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Bitterns, herons and egrets|Bitterns, herons and egrets]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Ibises and spoonbills|Ibises and spoonbills]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Storks|Storks]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Grebes|Grebes]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Buzzards, kites and allies|Buzzards, kites and allies]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Osprey|Osprey]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Falcons|Falcons]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Rails, crakes and coots|Rails, crakes and coots]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Cranes|Cranes]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Bustards|Bustards]]&nbsp;\u2022\n[[#Oystercatchers|Oystercatchers]]