n| [[Great reed warbler]]<br/>(''Acrocephalus arundinaceus'') ||<center>[[File:Acrocephalus arundinaceus adult NRM.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant, has bred\n|}\n\n==Cisticolas==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Cisticolidae]]\n\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Zitting cisticola]]<br/>(''Cisticola juncidis'') ||<center>[[File:Zitting Cisticola (Breeding plumage) I- Kolkata IMG 5046.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|}\n\n==Waxwings==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Bombycillidae]]\n\nThe waxwings are a group of passerine birds characterised by soft, silky plumage and unique red tips to some of the wing feathers. There are three species worldwide, two in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Cedar waxwing]]<br/>(''Bombycilla cedrorum'') ||<center>[[File:Cedar Waxwing August 14 2012 Newfoundland PA.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Bohemian waxwing]]<br/>(''Bombycilla garrulus'') ||<center>[[File:Bombycilla garrulusII.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A winter visitor in highly varied numbers.\n|}\n\n==Wallcreeper==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Wallcreeper|Tichodromadidae]]\n\nOne species, in its own family, a visitor to Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Wallcreeper]]<br/>(''Tichodroma muraria'') ||<center>[[File:Tichodroma muraria02 cropped.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|}\n\n==Nuthatches==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Nuthatch|Sittidae]]\n\nNuthatches are small woodland birds with the unusual ability to climb down trees head-first, unlike other birds which can only go upwards. There are about twenty-four species worldwide, two in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Red-breasted nuthatch]]<br/>(''Sitta canadensis'') ||<center>[[File:Sitta canadensis CT2.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Eurasian nuthatch]]<br/>(''Sitta europaea'') ||<center>[[File:Sitta europaea Luc Viatour.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|}\n\n==Treecreepers==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Treecreeper|Certhiidae]]\n\nTreecreepers are small woodland birds, brown above and white below. They have thin, pointed, down-curved bills, which they use to extricate insects from bark. There are seven species worldwide, two in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Common treecreeper]]<br/>(''Certhia familiaris'') ||<center>[[File:Certhia familiaris 01.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|-\n| [[Short-toed treecreeper]]<br/>(''Certhia brachydactyla'') ||<center>[[File:Boomkruiper1reversed.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|}\n\n==Wrens==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Troglodytidae]]\n\nWrens are small and inconspicuous birds, except for their loud songs. They have short wings and thin down-turned bills. There are about 80 species worldwide with one in Britain.\n\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Eurasian wren|Wren]]<br/>(''Troglodytes troglodytes'') ||<center>[[File:Eurasian-Wren-Troglodytes-troglodytes.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|}\n\n==Mockingbirds and allies==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Mimidae]]\n\nMedium-sized passerine birds with long tails. Some are notable for their ability to mimic sounds such as other birds' songs. There are about 35 species worldwide. Three have occurred as vagrants in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Northern mockingbird]]<br/>(''Mimus polyglottos'') ||<center>[[File:Mimus polyglottos -Krendle Woods, Cary, North Carolina, USA-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Brown thrasher]]<br/>(''Toxostoma rufum'') ||<center>[[File:Toxostoma rufum -Garland, Texas, USA-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant (one record)\n|-\n| [[Grey catbird]]<br/>(''Dumetella carolinensis'') ||<center>[[File:Dumetella carolinensis -Brendan T. Byrne State Forest, New Jersey, USA-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant (one record)\n|}\n\n==Starlings==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Starling|Sturnidae]]\n\nStarlings are small to medium-sized passerine birds with strong feet. Their flight is strong and direct and most are very gregarious. There are about 114 species worldwide with two in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Common starling]]<br/>(''Sturnus vulgaris'') ||<center>[[File:Colourful starling.jpeg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species and winter visitor\n|-\n| [[Rosy starling]]<br/>(''Pastor roseus'') ||<center>[[File:Rosy Starling (Sturnus roseus) near Hyderabad W2 IMG 4837.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|}\n\n==Dippers==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Dipper|Cinclidae]]\n\nDark, dumpy, aquatic birds which are able to forage for food on the beds of rivers. There are five species worldwide with one in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[White-throated dipper]]<br/>(''Cinclus cinclus'') ||<center>[[File:Cinclus cinclus -Kirkcudbright, Scotland-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species\n|}\n\n==Thrushes==\n'''Order''': [[passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Thrush_(bird)|Turdidae]]\n\nThe thrushes are plump, soft-plumaged, small to medium-sized insectivores or sometimes omnivores, often feeding on the ground. Many have attractive songs. There are about 183 species worldwide, 20 in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[White's thrush]]<br/>(''Zoothera dauma'') ||<center>[[File:Zoothera dauma - Ang Khang.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Varied thrush]]<br/>(''Ixoreus naevius'') ||<center>[[File:Zoothera naevia 31224.JPG|500x160px]]</center> || A very rare vagrant (one record)\n|-\n| [[Wood thrush]]<br/>(''Hylocichla mustelina'') ||<center>[[File:Hylocichla mustelina (cropped).jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Hermit thrush]]<br/>(''Catharus guttatus'') ||<center>[[File:Hermit thrush qmnonic.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Swainson's thrush]]<br/>(''Catharus ustulatus'') ||<center>[[File:Catharus ustulatus -North Dakota-8a.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Grey-cheeked thrush]]<br/>(''Catharus minimus'') ||<center>[[File:Graycheekedthrush36.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Veery]]<br/>(''Catharus fuscescens'') ||<center>[[File:Catharus fuscescens CT.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Siberian thrush]]<br/>(''Geokichla sibirica'') ||<center>[[File:Zoothera sibirica 431.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Ring ouzel]]<br/>(''Turdus torquatus'') ||<center>[[File:Ring Ouzel.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A breeding summer visitor\n|-\n| [[Common blackbird|Blackbird]]<br/>(''Turdus merula'') ||<center>[[File:Common Blackbird.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|-\n| [[Eyebrowed thrush]]<br/>(''Turdus obscurus'') ||<center>[[File:Eyebrowed Thrush.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Dusky thrush]]<br/>(''Turdus eunomus'') ||<center>[[File:Turdus eunomus -Japan-8.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Naumann's thrush]]<br/>(''Turdus naumanni'') ||<center>[[File:Bandong.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Black-throated thrush]]<br/>(''Turdus atrogularis'') ||<center>[[File:Turdusatro.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Red-throated thrush]]<br/>(''Turdus ruficollis'') ||<center>[[File:Dark Throated Thrush in Temple of Heaven.JPG|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Fieldfare]]<br/>(''Turdus pilaris'') ||<center>[[File:Turdus pilaris2.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A winter visitor, rare breeder\n|-\n| [[Song thrush]]<br/>(''Turdus philomelos'') ||<center>[[File:Song Thrush Turdus philomelos.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|-\n| [[Redwing]]<br/>(''Turdus iliacus'') ||<center>[[File:Redwing Turdus iliacus.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A winter visitor, rare breeder\n|-\n| [[Mistle thrush]]<br/>(''Turdus viscivorus'') ||<center>[[File:Turdus viscivorus in Baikonur-town 001.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A resident breeding species \n|-\n| [[American robin]]<br/>(''Turdus migratorius'') ||<center>[[File:Turdus-migratorius-002.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|}\n\n==Old World flycatchers and chats==\n'''Order''': [[Passerine|Passeriformes]]{{nbsp|3}}'''Family''': [[Old World flycatcher|Muscicapidae]]. Subfamily: [[Old World flycatcher|Muscicapinae]]\n\nThe flycatchers and chats are small, mainly insectivorous birds. The flycatchers fly out from a perch to catch insects in the air. There are about 297 species worldwide, 30 in Britain.\n{| width=90% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=25% | Common and binomial names\n!width=30% | Image\n!width=45% | Status\n|-\n| [[Rufous bush robin]]<br/>(''Cercotrichas galactotes'') ||<center>[[File:2009-red-backed-scrub-robin.jpg|500x160px]]</center> || A rare vagrant\n|-\n| [[Asian brown flycatcher